        <h1>Box and Whisker Plot</h1>

        <img class=3D"top_image" src=3D"https://datavizcatalogue.com/method=
s/images/top_images/box_plot.png" alt=3D"box plot">

        <br><br>
=09
	<div class=3D"left_column">
		<h2>Description</h2>
	=09
		<p class=3D"description">
		A Box and Whisker Plot (or Box Plot) is a convenient way of visually disp=
laying the data distribution through their quartiles.
		</p>
       =20
        <p class=3D"description">
        The lines extending parallel from the boxes are known as the =E2=80=
=9Cwhiskers=E2=80=9D, which are used to indicate variability outside the up=
per and lower quartiles. Outliers are sometimes plotted as individual dots =
that are in-line with whiskers. Box Plots can be drawn either vertically or=
 horizontally.
        </p>
       =20
		<p class=3D"description">
		Although Box Plots may seem primitive in comparison to a <a href=3D"https=
://datavizcatalogue.com/methods/histogram.html" style=3D"color: #FD6363;">H=
istogram</a> or <a href=3D"https://datavizcatalogue.com/methods/density_plo=
t.html" style=3D"color: #FD6363;">Density Plot</a>, they have the advantage=
 of taking up less space, which is useful when comparing distributions betw=
een many groups or datasets.
		</p>
       =20
		<p class=3D"description">
		Here are the types of observations one can make from viewing a Box Plot:
		</p>
	=09
		<p class=3D"listing">What the key values are, such as: the average, media=
n, 25th percentile, etc.</p>
		<p class=3D"listing">If there are any outliers and what their values are.=
</p>
		<p class=3D"listing">If the data is symmetrical or not.</p>
		<p class=3D"listing">How tightly is the data grouped.</p>
		<p class=3D"listing">If the data is skewed and if so, in what direction.<=
/p>
	=09
		<p class=3D"description">
		Two of the most commonly used variation of Box Plot are: variable-width B=
ox Plots and notched Box Plots.
        </p>
=09
		<br><br>

